title: For Sale/Trade:  Antique  Revolver's Smith & Wesson and more
postcontent: Hello everybody, up for grabs today is 3 antique revolver's all are near 100+ years old and in fair condition . I do not have a set price in mind so please make an fair offer cash or trade. I have only included one pic, but I can get many more on request. I'm an easy guy to deal with so please send any questions or concerns you may have. I received these on trade and they all belonged to someone's great grandfather. I have not shot any of these yet, but all look to be in safe firing condition, timing seems right and all cycle very well. If someone  doesn't snatch these soon I might test that theory;)#1 is a Smith and Wesson  Model 1903 hand ejector (bottom of pic). This firearm is chambered in 32 s&w long, a 6 shooter, and is a very early  variant from what I  can tell.  Serial number starts with 15xxx and I believe  it was shipped around 1908. This is the original nickel finish  and I would say it is 50 -60% Nice set of aftermarket  pearl grips, decent bore, locks up tight and timing seems dead on. No original box or papers but this really  is a dandy. I would feel confident shooting  this revolver, you can tell it was built very well. Someone who is a smith fan will enjoy this, built on the popular small frame.#2 is an H&R 5 shot, auto ejecting top break revolver chambered in 38 S&W. (Top of picture) this gun is also very solid, awesome bore and cylinders and much of the original blued finish remains. I'd say the finish is 80%+ with an awesome  patina. Bullseye target grips, with logo. Trigger is heavy on this guy, but again I would feel confident  shooting  this gun, timing  seems  correct and hammer drops hard. This is an antique gun but still in great shape. #3 is an very  old Iver Johson top break 32 caliber revolver. Nickel Finish is rough on this one with some rust on the external of gun. ( the bore and cylinders look great) has the old owl head grips and is a very compact revolver. This one I'm not sure about shooting condition.

title: For Sale:  Hammerli Virginian Revolvers .357 Mag. FTF in Indy
postcontent: Up for sale I have two Hammerli Virginian .357 mag. revolvers. These date from the mid 1970's, they were my Father's, he's been gone a year now. They both need repaired and both have the same issue. The cylinder will move when the revolvers are cocked. They both need a simple spring. I ordered some springs from Wolff. They are sear/bolt springs, they really are more like spring steel. These revolvers are Colt single action clones, the problem is they were only imported for about 2 years. The replacement springs I ordered do not have enough of a radius in them, they need bent a little more. I ordered a 3 pack of springs and have played around with one of the springs bending it, and have it working for the most part, but not completely. I'm selling these as a pair, AS IS, they need work. They are very collectible, and the pair I have are a barrel length that is even more collectible, they have 4 5/8's barrels. I remember as a kid and young man, we shot them, they have handling marks, nothing serious, but we did shoot them. The broken spring issue is quite common. The serial numbers are very close, they are not consecutive, but close. The boxes are rough but I do have them, I also have a target he sent to Hammerli, and a letter and pin that they sent him back. These are pretty cool revolvers and highly collectible. They have not been fired in at least 25 years. I'll assume if you are looking, then you know what they are. I have taken a bunch of pics, but armslist will only allow 3.More pics on request to serious buyers, no pic collectors please.I cannot accept any trade offers on these, if you email me with a trade offer do not expect a reply.Also if the ad is up, then yes they are still available, I will not respond to an email asking if I still have them.  My email has been spammed one too many times, and it is usually an email asking me if I still have something.Another note, I had to list them as Colt, they are Colt single action clones, but there isn't an option for Hammerli or Interarms.
